  "key_observations_html": "<aside class=\"crypto-story-callout\" aria-labelledby=\"key-obs-callout-title\"><p class=\"crypto-story-callout__title\" role=\"heading\" aria-level=\"3\" id=\"key-obs-callout-title\">Key observations</p><ul class=\"crypto-story-callout__list\"><li><strong>TMMF printed metrics were roughly flat this week:</strong> Distributed value near $12.95B (-1.1% 30D) leaves tokenized-cash balances largely range-bound\u2014the market story this week is more about issuer and distribution news than a shift in AUM. Related: <a href=\"https://thedefiant.io/converge/tradfi-and-fintech/jpmorgan-s-jltxx-tokenized-money-market-fund-aum-grows-250-in-a-month-on-ethereum\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">JPMorgan&#x27;s JLTXX Tokenized Money Market Fund AUM Grows 250% in a Month on Ethereum</a> (The Defiant).</li><li><strong>Early &quot;flight to efficiency&quot; shows up in TMMF 30D network share:</strong> Among tokenized money market funds, gainers include BNB Chain (+10.18% 30D TMMF network share), Avalanche C-Chain (+2.29% 30D TMMF network share); losers include Ethereum (-10.32% 30D TMMF network share), Aptos (-1.24% 30D TMMF network share). That pattern is consistent with TMMF issuers routing more distributed value toward higher-throughput, lower-fee chains\u2014though Ethereum still dominates TMMF share levels in most snapshots.</li><li><strong>Settlement economics are reshaping network share:</strong> Fee and throughput advantages can pull 30D network-share toward the chains that keep settlement cheaper and more operationally reliable. Related: <a href=\"https://www.coindesk.com/business/2026/07/20/bank-of-korea-prepares-for-live-cbdc-transactions-with-nine-banks-in-september\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Bank of Korea prepares for live CBDC transactions with 9 banks in September</a> (CoinDesk).</li><li><strong>Regulatory framing still decides product access:</strong> Similar funds can sit under different investor-eligibility and jurisdiction labels, so compliance framing still decides who can hold and distribute them. Related: <a href=\"https://www.coindesk.com/markets/2026/07/20/u-s-regulatory-developments-and-earnings-ecb-rate-decision-crypto-week-ahead\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">U.S. regulatory developments and earnings, ECB rate decision: Crypto Week Ahead</a> (CoinDesk).</li><li><strong>Issuer strategies are splitting into two models:</strong> <em>Institutional cash rail</em> programs (low holder counts, large AUM per holder\u2014e.g. USYC, BUIDL, iBENJI, USTB) vs <em>global yield / distribution</em> products (broader holder bases, retail- or UCITS-friendly framing\u2014e.g. USDY, WTGXX, BENJI, USTBL). These behave like different businesses under the same \"tokenized MMF\" label. Related: <a href=\"https://www.coindesk.com/business/2026/07/20/exodus-to-cut-25-of-global-workforce-in-payments-shift\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Exodus to cut 25% of global workforce in payments shift</a> (CoinDesk).</li></ul><p class=\"crypto-story-callout__note\">Context only\u2014not investment advice. Observations rank fund-level and network aggregates on this page against recent tokenization and money-market headlines. Bullets combine on-page data with recent industry headlines.</p></aside><p class=\"review-note ko-disclaimer\">Key observations are AI generated and should be reviewed for accuracy.</p>",
